Boil a large #pot{} of @water{2%l} for the @quinoa{170%grams}.

Stir in the quinoa and half the chicken stock and bring back to the boil. Cook
until the quinoa has doubled in size and the seed has visibly split, ~{12-15%mins}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pot, off the heat. Cover with a #lid{}
and set aside.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @shallot{1}(halved, peeled and chopped into
small pieces) into small pieces.

Trim the @green beans{75%grams}, then chop into thirds.

Chop the @broccolini{75%grams} into thirds.

Halve and deseed the @chilli{1}(halved and deseeded). Finely chop.

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the shallot and @diced Irish chicken breast{260%grams}. Season with salt
and pepper.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Cook, stirring occasionally, ~{6-8%mins}.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging used to keep it fresh.

Add @North Indian Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and half the chilli (use less if
you don't like spice). Fry for ~{1%min}.

Add green beans, broccolini, @Korma Curry Paste{1%sachet}, @creme fraiche{110%grams},
remaining @chicken stock{1%sachet}, @water{100%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp}.

> Double both water and sugar for 4 servings.

Cover and simmer until the chicken is cooked through, ~{5-7%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if needed. Once ready, season to taste
with salt and pepper.

Divide the quinoa between #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken curry.

Scatter over the remaining chilli (use less if you don't like spice).